\page andrepage Anomaly Detection and Removal (AnDRe)
\brief .


\tableofcontents

\section andreintro Introduction

This section explains \b AnDRe, the set of anomaly detection and
removal functions of \b Rack. A quick reference of all the commands is found in \ref commands_andre.

\subsection anomalies Background

Practically, echoes received by a weather radar originate not only
from precipitating clouds but also from insects, birds, aircraft,
ships, ground, sea clutter and electromagnetic emitters illustrated in the figure below.

\image html  radar-anomalies-compact2.png "Sources of anomalies." 
\image latex radar-anomalies-compact2.png "Sources of anomalies." width=0.5\textwidth

These external factors -- or anomalies from the meteorological point of view -- affect radar data in various ways. 
Some of the anomalies appear as distinct, localized peaks, some form geometrical patterns and some affect the overall data.
Examples of effects are shown in the image set below. 

\~exec
  make volumes-anom-panel.png 
\~

\image html  volumes-anom-panel.png "Samples containing several types of anomaly." width=90% 
\image latex volumes-anom-panel.png "Samples containing several types of anomaly." width=0.5\textwidth

\subsection andrecommands AnDRe commands

In AnDRe, the processing is divided into two stages: \b detecting anomalies and 
\b removing the anomalies from input data. 
In principle, these stages modify ODIM data independently so
a user may combine \b Rack with other software performing anomaly detection (see \ref file_quality).
The independence also means that anomalies can be detected using parallel computation in future versions
of \b Rack (see \ref  parallel_anom).

The following code is an example of applying both detection and removal in \b Rack :

\~exec
   ./make-andre.sh #exec
\~
\include andre-default-filled.and

By default, AnDRe commands apply to the full volume input. Each operator will look for quantities (typically DBZH) it needs
as input. To decrease computation time, the processing can be limited using \c --select command, for example:
\code
rack volume-anomalous.h5 --select 'dataset1:5/data1:3' <andre-cmds> ...
\endcode 
For details, see \ref selecting . 


The design of \b AnDRe detectors is based on \b Ropo , the operational anomaly detection C program applied in FMI since 2001.   
Each detector has been fully rewritten as a respective C++ class (rack::BiometOp, rack::EmitterOp, rack::ShipOp, rack::SpeckleOp)
which internally applies functions of the \b Drain library, for example segment size analysis, 
moving window filters and statistics. In development, emphasis has been on code re-usability, speed and stability; see
\ref andredetails "implementation details" 
further below.


\b Rack provides several detectors that compute detection fields ie. probablity images, explained next. 
The removal procedures are explained after that.

\section detectors Detection

Currently, \b AnDRe supports detection the following anomalies: 

-# birds and insects ("biometeors")
-# emitter lines
-# widespread electromagnetic interference (jamming)
-# ships
-# speckle noise 

\ref commands_andre start with \c '--a', and can be listed with 
\code
rack --help andre 
\endcode 



