\subsection aDopplerNoise Detecting variations in Doppler wind

Faster yet less accurate bird detection is available as \c aDopplerNoise which computes 
standard deviation much in the same way the corresponding meteorological motion product \ref dopplerDev .
It takes three parameters: speed \c threshold (m/s) as well as  window width and height. 
The obtained deviation is converted to a detection probability by means of a fuzzy bell function.

\~exec
./make-andre-example.sh anom-sea dopplerNoise #exec SITE=fikor 
\~
\include aDopplerNoise.exm
  
\image html  result-anom-sea-dopplerNoise.png "Detection results of \c --aDopplerNoise ."
\image latex result-anom-sea-dopplerNoise.png "Detection results of \c --aDopplerNoise ." width=0.5\textwidth


\subsection aEmitter Detecting emitters (electromagnetic interference)

AnDRe emitter detector takes four parameters: 
\c lengthMin (along the beam, kilometres), \c widthMax (azimuthal degrees) and \c sensitivity (between 0.0 and 1.0).
The current implementation applies median filtering twice on the data: horizontally and vertically. Then, the vertical result is
subtracted from the horizontal, revealing the horizontally elongated line segments. The computed medians are biased; instead of the
conventional median position (at 0.5 of the cumulative distribution) one may lighten or darken the results with the sensitivity value. A high value
darkens the vertical result and lightens the horizontal result, causing more line segments in the resulting detection field. 


\~exec
#
SITE=plrze ./make-andre-example.sh anom-emitter emitter=5,5,0.75 #exec
\~
\include aEmitter.exm

\image html  result-anom-emitter-emitter.png "Detection results of \c --aEmitter ." 
\image latex result-anom-emitter-emitter.png "Detection results of \c --aEmitter ." width=0.5\textwidth


\subsection aJamming Detecting jamming

In presense of intensive nearby transmitters or receiver malfunction radar data can be contaminated by intensive overall 
noise. \b Rack models the shape of such intensity as a function of distance and applies curve fitting to distinguish
between smoothly matching noise areas and pronounced meteorological targets.

\~exec
./make-andre-example.sh anom-calib    jamming1    #exec SITE=lvrix 
./make-andre-example.sh anom-jamming  jamming2    #exec SITE=fikor 
\~
\include aJamming.exm

\image html  result-anom-calib-jamming1.png "Detection results of \c --aJamming ." 
\image latex result-anom-calib-jamming1.png "Detection results of \c --aJamming ." width=0.5\textwidth

\image html  result-anom-jamming-jamming2.png "Detection results of \c --aJamming ." 
\image latex result-anom-jamming-jamming2.png "Detection results of \c --aJamming ." width=0.5\textwidth




\subsection aNonMet Detecting sea clutter and other non-meteorogical targets

With the polarimetric quantity \em RhoHV one can easily detect some non-meteorological echoes such as sea clutter.
For meteorological targets, \em RhoHV is close to 1.0 and below otherwise. For example, sea clutter can be detected with 
the following command:

\~exec
./make-andre-example.sh anom-sea nonMet        #exec SITE=fikor 
\~
\include aNonMet.exm

\image html  result-anom-sea-nonMet.png "Detection results of \c --aNonMet ." 
\image latex result-anom-sea-nonMet.png "Detection results of \c --aNonMet ." width=0.5\textwidth


 
\subsection aShip  Detecting ships

The ship detector takes four parameters: 
\c minDBZ (minimum reflectance), 
\c devDBZ (minimum reflectance difference in a neighborhood),
\c windowWidth (neighbourhood's beam-directional width, metres), 
\c windowHeight (neighbourhood's azimuthal width, degrees).
First, the detector function computes two separate fields: a fuzzy remapping of  \c minDBZ and 
field resulting from high-pass filtering with given neighbourhood. Basically, the result is a fuzzy multiplication of those.  
In addition, artificial vertical "ship sidelobes" are computed for the latter field, modelling 
the radar echoes of highly reflective point targets. If the sidelobes also appear in 
the fuzzy intensity field, they become included in the final result.

\~exec
./make-andre-example.sh anom-sea ship #exec 
\~
\include aShip.exm
  
\image html  result-anom-sea-ship.png "Detection results of \c --aShip ."
\image latex result-anom-sea-ship.png "Detection results of \c --aShip ." width=0.5\textwidth


\subsection aSpeckle Detecting speckle noise

Speckle detection needs two parameters: \c threshold (in dBZ) and \c area (fuzzy maximal speck size). 
This detector focuses on distinct, small specks, giving maximum value to single-pixel segments, and progressively smaller values
for larger segments. The speckle detector applies a semi-recursive flood-fill type
function in computing segment sizes: the image is traversed and each segment having intensity 
of at least \c threshold becomes analyzed. The size of each segment fuzzily converted to an intensity of equally shaped segment
in the result image. 

\~exec
./make-andre-example.sh anom-sea   speckle1=-10,invertPolar=false #exec  
./make-andre-example.sh anom-sea   speckle2=-10,invertPolar=true #exec
convert +append anom-sea-panel.png andre-anom-sea-speckle{1,2}-panel.png -filter point -filter point -resize '347x600!' result-anom-sea-speckle.png
./make-andre-example.sh anom-noise speckle3=-10 #exec  
\~
\include aSpeckle.exm

\image html  result-anom-noise-speckle3.png "Detection results of \c --aSpeckle ."
\image latex result-anom-noise-speckle3.png "Detection results of \c --aSpeckle ." width=0.5\textwidth
 
The speck areas are optionally scaled to Cartesian coordinate system. Unscaled areas are better for detecting for non-physical, range independent anomalies
like noise whereas scaled mode should be used if physical targets are focused.  
 
 
\image html  result-anom-sea-speckle.png "Detection results of \c --aSpeckle without and with polar coordinate inversion."
\image latex result-anom-sea-speckle.png "Detection results of \c --aSpeckle without and with polar coordinate inversion." width=0.5\textwidth





\subsection aSun "Detecting" the Sun

This detector calculates the position of the Sun and marks its with sector of 
given width and intensity. The detector does not analyse the data itself; 
sectors will be marked also inside precipitation. 


\~exec
./make-andre-example.sh anom-sea sun #exec SITE=fikor 
\~
\include aSun.exm
  
\image html  result-anom-sea-sun.png "Detection results of \c --aSun ."
\image latex result-anom-sea-sun.png "Detection results of \c --aSun ." width=0.5\textwidth





 
\section andreCumulation  Cumulating quality fields

 Typically, user wants to detect several different types of anomalies.
In the ODIM structure, \b Rack creates new data arrays for storing detection results:
-# An overall result (maximum) of all the detection operators executed, stored in 
   \c /dataset??/data??/quality1,  with \c what:quantity=QIND
-# If \c --store INTERMEDIATE has been called, all the intermediate detection results    
   in \c /dataset??/data??/quality{N} where \c {N} is an index starting from 2, with \c what:quantity=PROB-xxx (non-standard)

\b Universality. Some detectors like \c --aSpeckle are \em universal , they apply not only for the quantity they have been computed on (like \c DBZH)
but also other quantities (like \c VRAD). The resulting quality information is stored respectively to dataset level or data level.
This policy can be toggled with \c --aUniversal .
    
The resulting cumulative field with \c what:quantity=QIND is inverted, reflecting the probability of \em meteorological echoes, ie. quality of the data.
In parallel, the classification field with  \c what:quantity=CLASS is updated. 
The fields are updated automatically after every detection command. They reside on the dataset level or data level, depending on detector universality
described above. 

In the removal stage, \b AnDRe combines the \c QIND and \c CLASS fields automatically. One may also combine the fields with \c --aCombine .


\image html  andre-detected-hdfview.png "Cumulative field (top window) and distinct detection results (underlying windows)." 
\image latex andre-detected-hdfview.png "Cumulative field (top window) and distinct detection results (underlying windows)." width=0.9\textwidth

\section andreremoval  Anomaly removal

After applying preferred detectors, original data in the volume 
can be enhanced with the help of the overall quality field,
\c /dataset1/quality/data .

There are three techniques available for the removal:
-# erasing: replacing values with \c nodata 
-# damping: turning values down
-# gap filling: replacing values with surrounding values having better quality

\~exec
# ack volume-anomalous.h5  --aStore --aSpeckle '' --aEmitter '' --aShip '' --aBiomet '' -o andre-detected.h5
# ack volume-anom-sea.h5   --aStore --aBiomet '' --aEmitter '' --aJamming '' --aShip '' --aSpeckle ''  -o andre-detected.h5 
\~

The \c --aRemover command simply replaces data values with \c nodata in locations where the quality (anomaly probability) is lower than a threshold:
\code
rack volume-anomalous.h5  <...detection commands...> --aRemover 0.5  -o andre-removed.h5
\endcode
By default, \c aRemover applies to practically all quantities (DBZH,TH,VRAD,RHOHV,...). This behaviour can be changed with \c --select command.  

\~exec
./make-andre-remover-example.sh anom-sea remover=0.25  remover=0.75 #exec SITE=fikor
\~
\image html  volume-anom-sea-remover-panel.png  "A sweep corrected by \c --aRemover with threshold 0.25 (left) and 0.75 (right)."
\image latex volume-anom-sea-remover-panel.png  "A sweep corrected by \c --aRemover with threshold 0.25 (left) and 0.75 (right)." width=0.5\textwidth 



A smooth erasure function is implemented as \c --aDamper which decreases intensity proportionally to the quality index. It applies to reflectivity
data (DBZH) only. The lower the quality index, the more intensity will be decreased. 
An example of the erasing approach:
\code
rack volume-anomalous.h5  <...detection commands...> --aDamper 0.5 -o andre-damped.h5
\endcode

The parameter defines the threshold quality. The bin values below the quality threshold will be smoothly erased.

\~exec
./make-andre-remover-example.sh anom-sea damper=0.25  damper=0.75 #exec SITE=fikor 
\~
\image html  volume-anom-sea-damper-panel.png  "A sweep corrected by \c --aDamper with threshold 0.25 (left) and 0.5 (right)."
\image latex volume-anom-sea-damper-panel.png  "A sweep corrected by \c --aDamper with threshold 0.25 (left) and 0.5 (right)." width=0.5\textwidth 


Gap filling means replacing single values with neighboring, more reliable values. 
An example of the gap filling approach:
\code
rack volume-anomalous.h5  <...detection commands...>  --aGapFill 2000m,5deg  -o andre-gapfilled.h5
\endcode

The parameters of \c aGapFill are window width and height as metres and azimuthal degrees, respectively. 
Internally, this operator is implemented using 8-directional \em distance \em transform. 

\~exec
# SITE=fikor 
./make-andre-remover-example.sh anom-sea gapFill=1500,3 gapFill=2500,7 #exec
\~
\image html  volume-anom-sea-gapFill-panel.png  "A sweep corrected with gap fill parameters 1500m,3deg (left) and 2500m,7deg (right)."
\image latex volume-anom-sea-gapFill-panel.png  "A sweep corrected with gap fill parameters 1500m,3deg (left) and 2500m,7deg (right)."  width=0.5\textwidth 

Another, experimental gap filling operator \c --aGapFillRec is recursive and produces spline-like correction fields. The result is smoother but 
slower to compute. Internally, this operator is implemented by repeating a weighted averaging window.   

The removal command can be applied together, for example:
\code
rack volume-anomalous.h5  <...detection commands...>  --aDamper 0.5,0.1  --aGapFill 1500m,7deg  -o andre-corrected.h5
\endcode


\~rema
 #ack andre-detected.h5 --aDamper 0.5,0.1  --aGapFill 2000m,5deg  -o andre-cleaned.png 
 #onvert +append -frame 1  volume-anomalous.png andre-cleaned.png -resize 75%  andre-all.png 
 #image latex  andre-all.png "A sweep (left) and its corrected version using remover and gap filling (right)." 
 #image html  andre-all.png "A sweep (left) and its corrected version using remover and gap filling (right)." width=0.5\textwidth
\~



\section otherQuality  Other quality fields

Detection based quality fields like the ones explained above describe the probability of signals originating from
other than desired targets (other than precipitation, typically). In addition to those, \b Rack provides
two operators that describe the quality. 


\subsection aAttenuation  Attenuation in rain

Radar signal attenuates in heavy rain. The amount of attenuation in liquid rain can be approximated from dBZ data using
formula proposed by Ulrich Blahak:
\f[
     k(Z) = 1.12\cdot10^{-4} Z_e^{0.62}
\f]
 
\~exec
./make-andre-example.sh anom-attn    attenuation1 #exec  SITE=fivan 
./make-andre-example.sh anom-clutter attenuation2 #exec SITE=fivim 
\~
\include aAttenuation.exm

\image html  result-attenuation1.png "Detection results of \c --aAttenuation ." 
\image latex result-attenuation1.png "Detection results of \c --aAttenuation ." width=0.5\textwidth

\image html  result-attenuation2.png "Detection results of \c --aAttenuation ." 
\image latex result-attenuation2.png "Detection results of \c --aAttenuation ." width=0.5\textwidth


Note that this field should NOT be used for removing echoes; the radar has already cleaned data in signal processor.
However, this operator should be computed after removal operators (if applied). The resulting (total) quality field 
can be used in further production, 
like quality based compositing in which input bins of lower quality will be overridden by other, overlapping bins of higher quality. 



\subsection aCCor  Using Doppler filtering result

If both the total reflectivity (\c TH ) and Doppler filtered reflectivity are available, their difference provides
information where the radar has detected static i.e. suspicious targets.  The \c CCor operator computes
the diffence between these and fuzzifies the result such that at the given threshold reflecitivy difference the
probability of anomaly is 0.5. 

\~exec
./make-andre-example.sh anom-sea cCor #exec SITE=fikor 
\~
\include aCCor.exm

\image html  result-cCor.png "Detection results of \c --aCCor ." 
\image latex result-cCor.png "Detection results of \c --aCCor ." width=0.5\textwidth

Note that this field should NOT be used for removing echoes; the radar has already cleaned data in signal processor.
However, this operator should be computed after removal operators (if applied). The resulting (total) quality field 
can be used in further production, 
like quality based compositing in which input bins of lower quality will be overridden by other, overlapping bins of higher quality. 

\subsection aTime  Timing based quality

Likewise, we can associate timing based quality field that describes the extent in which each measurement bin is representative of
the nomimal time of the volume or some other desired time, like the nominal time of a composite. 
 
\~exec
SITE=fikor ./make-andre-example.sh anom-sea time=20130504023010,1,5 #exec
\~

\include aTime.exm
  
\image html  result-time.png "'Detection' results of \c --aTime ."
\image latex result-time.png "'Detection' results of \c --aTime ." width=0.5\textwidth





*/